UNIT 2: BASIC DOCKER COMMANDS NOTES (WITH COMMAND EXAMPLES)

1.  Check Docker Version Command: docker –version

Example Output: Docker version 18.09.6

2.  Docker Info Command: docker info

Example: Shows containers, images, storage driver, etc.


3.  Docker History Command: docker history httpd

Example: Shows layers and size of httpd image


4.  Pull Image from Docker Hub Command: docker pull httpd

Example: Downloads Apache HTTP server image


5.  List Docker Images Command: docker images

Example Output: REPOSITORY TAG IMAGE ID SIZE


6.  Docker Run Command

Syntax: docker run [OPTIONS] IMAGE [COMMAND]

Common Options: -it → Interactive mode -d → Background mode –name →
Assign name –rm → Remove container automatically -p → Port mapping -e →
Environment variable -v → Volume mount


Examples:

1.  Simple Run: docker run httpd

2.  Run with command: docker run httpd echo “Hello World”

3.  Run with name: docker run –name my-container httpd

4.  Run interactive + background: docker run -it -d httpd

7.  Environment Variables

Command: docker run -e MY_VAR=value httpd env

Example: docker run -it -e MY_NAME=Harpreet ubuntu bash echo $MY_NAME

Multiple Variables: docker run -e APP_ENV=production -e APP_VERSION=1.0
nginx

Using .env file: docker run –env-file .env myapp

8.  Port Mapping

Syntax: docker run -p HOST_PORT:CONTAINER_PORT IMAGE

Example: docker run -p 8080:80 nginx

Access in browser: http://localhost:8080

9.  List Containers

Running Containers: docker ps

All Containers: docker ps -a

10. Execute Command Inside Container

Command: docker exec -it bash

Example: docker exec -it abc123 bash

11. Task Example

Run Ubuntu with environment variable: docker run -it -e COLLEGE=CSE
ubuntu bash

Check variable: echo $COLLEGE

IMPORTANT NOTES: - Environment variables exist only inside container -
They disappear after container stops - Containers are isolated from host
system
